content.problemStatement:
The **break statement** in a switch statement is used to terminate the execution of the switch case block. It prevents the program from **falling through** to the next case and ensures that only the code corresponding to the matching case is executed.

**Syntax:**
```java
switch (expression) {
    case value1:
        // Code to execute if the expression matches value1
        break;  // Exit the switch statement
    case value2:
        // Code to execute if the expression matches value2
        break;
    case value3:
        // Code to execute if the expression matches value3
        break;
    default:
        // Code to execute if no case matches
        break;
}
```

---

**Example:**
```java
class Seedit {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Initialize the variable 'month' with a predefined value (2 represents February)
        int month = 2;

        // Use a switch statement to determine and print the name of the month
        switch (month) {
            case 1: // If 'month' equals 1
                System.out.println("January"); // Print "January"
                break; // Exit the switch statement after executing this case

            case 2: // If 'month' equals 2
                System.out.println("February"); // Print "February"
                break; // Exit the switch statement after executing this case

            case 3: // If 'month' equals 3
                System.out.println("March"); // Print "March"
                break; // Exit the switch statement after executing this case
        }
    }
}

```
**Expected Output:**
```default
February
```

